FAVOURITE CHARACTERS OF ALLLLL TIIIIIIIME list

Spider-man - retains his place as the best of the best of the best

tumblr.caption:
thecomicsvault:

TODAY IN COMIC BOOK HISTORY: January 10, 1962

The original Ant-Man, Dr. Henry Johnathan “Hank” Pym made his debut in Tales To Astonish #27 as a scientist testing a shrinking apparatus on himself and then having to fend off ants until he could return to normal height. The story was more of a sci-fi/horror/fantasy story, which is what TTA was during the transition from the Golden to Silver Age of comics.

Eight issues later, Dr. Pym came back. This time as a superhero using his shrinking technology to fight crime. The addition of a helmet that could communicate and control ants made it so hostile insects were the least of his problems. Ant-Man took over the title full time and soon Pym’s lab assistant and girlfriend, Janet van Dyne aka The Wasp, joined him in #44 and the two spent the next 20+ issues solving crimes. Ant-Man eventually became Giant-Man during their run, one of many of Pym’s aliases.

Pym and van Dyne are founding members of The Avengers and were big parts of the early stories. They left the team briefly only to return for one of the most iconic Avengers stories. Pym was the sole creator of the artificial intelligence known as Ultron. Originally created for non-lethal purposes, Ultron gained sentience and a hatred for all organic life. He became one of Marvel’s biggest villains. Out of that story line also came a new Avenger, The Vision, created by Ultron to defeat The Avengers. He eventually turned on his creator. Ultron and Pym have the strngest father-son relationships in comics.

Hank is also know for his various alter-egos, By the late-60s he had already been Ant-Man, Giant Man and Goliath. The constant shape-changing, overusing his serums and various costumes caused him to develop schizophrenia. In another iconic Avengers story Hank is seemingly killed by a new costumed hero, Yellowkacket. Only The Wasp knew it was really Pym and the two, after years of romantic tension, finally married. 

After taking another break from The Avengers, Pym returns. However his personality has regressed even further. He shows more hostility towards Janet and continues to beat villains after they are defeated. This causes Captain America to suspend him from the team until after the verdict of his court-martial. This pushes Pym to the breaking point and he has a complete mental breakdown. Devising a plan to attack the courthouse during his trial using a robot which he will defeat and make himself look like the hero. Janet discovers his plan and he infamously strikes her.

The two eventually divorce and Pym is takes a break from superheroics for a bit. He then joins the West Coast Avengers before returning to The Avengers. Pym has passed down some of his aliases. First Giant-Man and Goliath to Dr. Bill Foster aka Black Goliath. Next he passed his alter-ego Ant-Man to Scott Lang after he stole the costume and Pym particles to help his daughter. 

Hank Pym has been a part of almost every major Marvel event since the beginning and his influence in the Marvel Universe is far-reaching. He’s one of the great comic book characters to portray the inner conflict of someone who wants to do the right thing but doesn’t always due to mental disorders or misguided intentions. He’s also a great character period.

thecomicsvault:

TODAY IN COMIC BOOK HISTORY: January 10, 1962

The original Ant-Man, Dr. Henry Johnathan “Hank” Pym made his debut in Tales To Astonish #27 as a scientist testing a shrinking apparatus on himself and then having to fend off ants until he could return to normal height. The story was more of a sci-fi/horror/fantasy story, which is what TTA was during the transition from the Golden to Silver Age of comics.

Eight issues later, Dr. Pym came back. This time as a superhero using his shrinking technology to fight crime. The addition of a helmet that could communicate and control ants made it so hostile insects were the least of his problems. Ant-Man took over the title full time and soon Pym’s lab assistant and girlfriend, Janet van Dyne aka The Wasp, joined him in #44 and the two spent the next 20+ issues solving crimes. Ant-Man eventually became Giant-Man during their run, one of many of Pym’s aliases.

Pym and van Dyne are founding members of The Avengers and were big parts of the early stories. They left the team briefly only to return for one of the most iconic Avengers stories. Pym was the sole creator of the artificial intelligence known as Ultron. Originally created for non-lethal purposes, Ultron gained sentience and a hatred for all organic life. He became one of Marvel’s biggest villains. Out of that story line also came a new Avenger, The Vision, created by Ultron to defeat The Avengers. He eventually turned on his creator. Ultron and Pym have the strngest father-son relationships in comics.

Hank is also know for his various alter-egos, By the late-60s he had already been Ant-Man, Giant Man and Goliath. The constant shape-changing, overusing his serums and various costumes caused him to develop schizophrenia. In another iconic Avengers story Hank is seemingly killed by a new costumed hero, Yellowkacket. Only The Wasp knew it was really Pym and the two, after years of romantic tension, finally married. 

After taking another break from The Avengers, Pym returns. However his personality has regressed even further. He shows more hostility towards Janet and continues to beat villains after they are defeated. This causes Captain America to suspend him from the team until after the verdict of his court-martial. This pushes Pym to the breaking point and he has a complete mental breakdown. Devising a plan to attack the courthouse during his trial using a robot which he will defeat and make himself look like the hero. Janet discovers his plan and he infamously strikes her.

The two eventually divorce and Pym is takes a break from superheroics for a bit. He then joins the West Coast Avengers before returning to The Avengers. Pym has passed down some of his aliases. First Giant-Man and Goliath to Dr. Bill Foster aka Black Goliath. Next he passed his alter-ego Ant-Man to Scott Lang after he stole the costume and Pym particles to help his daughter. 

Hank Pym has been a part of almost every major Marvel event since the beginning and his influence in the Marvel Universe is far-reaching. He’s one of the great comic book characters to portray the inner conflict of someone who wants to do the right thing but doesn’t always due to mental disorders or misguided intentions. He’s also a great character period.

I’d give anything to see her in a movie.

Oh my gosh yes

YES someone else who loves the White Rabbit :D

She’s my favourite Spidey villain ever and the three stories she got to star in are some of the actual best okay

I would pay good money to see her be the villain of a live action Spiderman film, in all her evil bunny girl glory

They also need to include her fluffy rocket boots, her deadly umbrella, her Bunnymobile and her giant robot bunny-bot that she had built

All of which she affords because she is an actual billionaire, like she doesn’t do crime for the money or to take over the world she was just super rich and bored and so decided it would be exciting to dress up like a bunny and become a supervillain

That’s her whole origin and I love it :D

So, she’s basically a reversal of Batman?

PRETTY MUCH

It is unknown if a bunny hopped through her window and inspired her to choose this as her costume/gimmick though

But I choose to believe one did…

tumblr.caption:
ryannorth:

Our first issue is out today!!  You can get Unbeatable Squirrel Girl at your local comic book store, you can download a digital copy RIGHT NOW, and/or you can get them in the mail!  DID YOU KNOW: the more copies we sell (whether physical or digital), the better chance we have of getting to make this comic forever and ever??

And on the off chance you don’t want to risk getting this book without some non-me people telling you they think the book is PRETTY OKAY, I have some good news!  Here’s a…

REVIEW ROUNDUP

COMICOSITY:

One word: adorbs.

OK, I’ll throw in a few more words. How about super-fun? Or unexpected? Or laugh-out-loud funny?

Some of those are compounds.

COMIC VINE:

Expectations were pretty high for this first issue but THE UNBEATABLE SQUIRREL GIRL exceeds them. North, Henderson, and Renzi have put together something that appeals to both young and old that is an incredible amount of fun, featuring a great, stand-out star…

THE BEAT:

…fun is no longer such a terrible word.The Unbeatable Squirrel Girl is a product of this shift, something steadfast and confident in its construction and delivery, an unapologetic take on the pyjama drama as a source of unfettered joy. 

CBR:

There are few “perfect issues” in a year of comics and yet here I am, first week of January writing about another one… There is not one missed or false note, it’s a totally cohesive vision. Everyone creating this book knows exactly what they want it to be and exactly how to get it there.

COMICBOOK.COM

…one of the most fun debuts published by Marvel Comics in a very long time. If you’re looking for a comic that you can share with anyone or that will cheer you up after a major bummer of a day, this is it. At the end of The Unbeatable Squirrel Girl #1 there is only one question worth asking: When does #2 come out?

I hope you enjoy the book!  Next month even crazier things happen.  UNTIL THEN I PROPOSE WE ALL:

  1. EAT NUTS
  2. KICK BUTTS

tumblr.caption:
thecomicsvault:

TODAY IN COMIC BOOK HISTORY: January 10, 1962

The original Ant-Man, Dr. Henry Johnathan “Hank” Pym made his debut in Tales To Astonish #27 as a scientist testing a shrinking apparatus on himself and then having to fend off ants until he could return to normal height. The story was more of a sci-fi/horror/fantasy story, which is what TTA was during the transition from the Golden to Silver Age of comics.

Eight issues later, Dr. Pym came back. This time as a superhero using his shrinking technology to fight crime. The addition of a helmet that could communicate and control ants made it so hostile insects were the least of his problems. Ant-Man took over the title full time and soon Pym’s lab assistant and girlfriend, Janet van Dyne aka The Wasp, joined him in #44 and the two spent the next 20+ issues solving crimes. Ant-Man eventually became Giant-Man during their run, one of many of Pym’s aliases.

Pym and van Dyne are founding members of The Avengers and were big parts of the early stories. They left the team briefly only to return for one of the most iconic Avengers stories. Pym was the sole creator of the artificial intelligence known as Ultron. Originally created for non-lethal purposes, Ultron gained sentience and a hatred for all organic life. He became one of Marvel’s biggest villains. Out of that story line also came a new Avenger, The Vision, created by Ultron to defeat The Avengers. He eventually turned on his creator. Ultron and Pym have the strngest father-son relationships in comics.

Hank is also know for his various alter-egos, By the late-60s he had already been Ant-Man, Giant Man and Goliath. The constant shape-changing, overusing his serums and various costumes caused him to develop schizophrenia. In another iconic Avengers story Hank is seemingly killed by a new costumed hero, Yellowkacket. Only The Wasp knew it was really Pym and the two, after years of romantic tension, finally married. 

After taking another break from The Avengers, Pym returns. However his personality has regressed even further. He shows more hostility towards Janet and continues to beat villains after they are defeated. This causes Captain America to suspend him from the team until after the verdict of his court-martial. This pushes Pym to the breaking point and he has a complete mental breakdown. Devising a plan to attack the courthouse during his trial using a robot which he will defeat and make himself look like the hero. Janet discovers his plan and he infamously strikes her.

The two eventually divorce and Pym is takes a break from superheroics for a bit. He then joins the West Coast Avengers before returning to The Avengers. Pym has passed down some of his aliases. First Giant-Man and Goliath to Dr. Bill Foster aka Black Goliath. Next he passed his alter-ego Ant-Man to Scott Lang after he stole the costume and Pym particles to help his daughter. 

Hank Pym has been a part of almost every major Marvel event since the beginning and his influence in the Marvel Universe is far-reaching. He’s one of the great comic book characters to portray the inner conflict of someone who wants to do the right thing but doesn’t always due to mental disorders or misguided intentions. He’s also a great character period.

tumblr.body:
Rules: Always post the rules. Answer the questions the person who tagged you asked, then write 11 new ones.

Thanks faceofthebovvered for tagging me :D

1. Least favourite character from The Hobbit?

Film or book? Film: Alfrid. Book: hnnng this is difficult.

2. Least favourite character from Harry Potter?

Dolores Umbridge. Even though she’s the character we all love to hate.

3. Least favourite character from Marvel?

Another difficult one. Mr. Fantastic from the Fantastic Four. Just can’t stand him.

4. Least favourite sport?

I can’t think of my least favourite sport. I’m kind of ‘eh’ towards all forms of sport except rugby ‘cause that’s awesome.

5. Which good book was made into a really really bad film?

Percy Jackson and the Sea of Monsters. What a terrible, terrible film.

6. First book that made a huge impact on you?

The Color Purple by Alice Walker. I’d seen the film before reading the book, but the book made a much bigger impact on me.

7. Is there something you want to do differently in 2015?

Yes, I would like to be more neat. Clean my house more often. This will probably not happen…

8. What is your main goal for 2015?

Get my bachelor’s degree.

9. What is the last thing you cooked/baked?

I last cooked stuff to put in a tortilla, and I last baked cupcakes.

10. Do you have nice neighbours?

I don’t know, I never see them. Except for twili-q, who lives right above me <3

11. Best youtubevideo ever?

No contest. This one.

And I will not add questions because you tagged everyone I know, faceofthebovvered.

tumblr.caption:
anti-stand-with-ward:

A week designed for people who adore the canonical villain that Ward is to come together and appreciate his vast creepiness.

Day 1: Favorite Villainous Moment
What Ward moment scared you the most? What moment solidified his villainy in your mind? What were your favorite moments of the team reacting to his villainy?

Day 2: Most Badass Moment
A moment Ward gets his ass kicked by somebody he’s wronged

Day 3: Parallels
How does Ward not measure up to other Marvel (or otherwise) heroes? How is he similar to other villains?

Day 4: Why He Doesn’t Deserve Redemption
Talk about the horrible things he has done, and how it makes it clear he is not a good person and doesn’t deserve redemption

Day 5: The Future
What would you like to see happen next?

Day 6: Alternate Universes
Create an AU where Ward meets and works with another villain from the MCU or any other story.

Day 7: Brett Dalton Appreciation
Appreciation for Brett Dalton’s marvelous performances after the Hydra reveal. What moment made you realize how good of an actor he is?

Hey everybody!  I've been talking with some people, and we thought it would a really cool idea to have a MARVEL MOVIE MARATHON!!!!  The idea is to watch 1 Marvel movie every week this semester leading up into Avengers 2, which comes out this May!  

So those of you who don't know anything about the Marvel Superheroes, now is your chance to find out more about them!

We will start off with IRON MAN tonight at 8:00 at the Honors House.  

Don't worry if you can't make it tonight, especially if you have seen the movies before.  We are going to watch them in chronological order from when the movies were made.  This would also be a great time to invite friends outside of CRU to join.  Thanks, and we hope to see you there!

thecomicsvault:

TODAY IN COMIC BOOK HISTORY: January 10, 1962

The original Ant-Man, Dr. Henry Johnathan “Hank” Pym made his debut in Tales To Astonish #27 as a scientist testing a shrinking apparatus on himself and then having to fend off ants until he could return to normal height. The story was more of a sci-fi/horror/fantasy story, which is what TTA was during the transition from the Golden to Silver Age of comics.

Eight issues later, Dr. Pym came back. This time as a superhero using his shrinking technology to fight crime. The addition of a helmet that could communicate and control ants made it so hostile insects were the least of his problems. Ant-Man took over the title full time and soon Pym’s lab assistant and girlfriend, Janet van Dyne aka The Wasp, joined him in #44 and the two spent the next 20+ issues solving crimes. Ant-Man eventually became Giant-Man during their run, one of many of Pym’s aliases.

Pym and van Dyne are founding members of The Avengers and were big parts of the early stories. They left the team briefly only to return for one of the most iconic Avengers stories. Pym was the sole creator of the artificial intelligence known as Ultron. Originally created for non-lethal purposes, Ultron gained sentience and a hatred for all organic life. He became one of Marvel’s biggest villains. Out of that story line also came a new Avenger, The Vision, created by Ultron to defeat The Avengers. He eventually turned on his creator. Ultron and Pym have the strngest father-son relationships in comics.

Hank is also know for his various alter-egos, By the late-60s he had already been Ant-Man, Giant Man and Goliath. The constant shape-changing, overusing his serums and various costumes caused him to develop schizophrenia. In another iconic Avengers story Hank is seemingly killed by a new costumed hero, Yellowkacket. Only The Wasp knew it was really Pym and the two, after years of romantic tension, finally married. 

After taking another break from The Avengers, Pym returns. However his personality has regressed even further. He shows more hostility towards Janet and continues to beat villains after they are defeated. This causes Captain America to suspend him from the team until after the verdict of his court-martial. This pushes Pym to the breaking point and he has a complete mental breakdown. Devising a plan to attack the courthouse during his trial using a robot which he will defeat and make himself look like the hero. Janet discovers his plan and he infamously strikes her.

The two eventually divorce and Pym is takes a break from superheroics for a bit. He then joins the West Coast Avengers before returning to The Avengers. Pym has passed down some of his aliases. First Giant-Man and Goliath to Dr. Bill Foster aka Black Goliath. Next he passed his alter-ego Ant-Man to Scott Lang after he stole the costume and Pym particles to help his daughter. 

Hank Pym has been a part of almost every major Marvel event since the beginning and his influence in the Marvel Universe is far-reaching. He’s one of the great comic book characters to portray the inner conflict of someone who wants to do the right thing but doesn’t always due to mental disorders or misguided intentions. He’s also a great character period.

ON THIS DATE (38 YEARS AGO)
January 10, 1977 - Ramones: Leave Home is released.
# ALL THINGS MUSIC PLUS+ 5/5 (MUST-HAVE!)
# Allmusic 4.5/5
# Rolling Stone (see original review below)

Leave Home is the second studio album by the Ramones, released on January 10, 1977. It reached #148 on the Billboard 200 Top LP's chart.

Released only months after their debut, the Ramones' second album pales slightly in comparison to its stone-classic predecessor--but only slightly. Leave Home contains enough all-time Ramones anthems - "Commando," "Pinhead" (which introduces the legendary "Gabba Gabba Hey" chant), and "Gimme Gimme Shock Treatment," to name only three--that it's still an essential document of the New York punk scene. Half the tracks don't even hit the two-minute mark--the longest is "Beat on the Brat," an epic 2:36--and the whole thing is over in under half an hour. Years of hardcore punk and the ever-increasing BPMs of underground dance music mean that this stuff doesn't sound as shockingly speedy now as it did at the time; what's surprising is how cheerful and poppy this allegedly transgressive music comes across, and how unexpectedly tight and well-rehearsed the supposedly sloppy band is. 

ORIGINAL ROLLING STONE REVIEW
These bands achieved their initial notoriety while playing in the same place (an esophagus of a bar called CBGB, in lower Manhattan) and have been lumped together with other habitués of this joint as purveyors of "punk rock." In their self-consciousness and liberal open-mindedness, these bands are as punky as Fonzie: that is, not at all.

Blondie is a quintet which juggles genres of fast rock, from a thick, Spector-ish vision of street crime called "X Offender" to a thick, Who-like vision of womanhood called "Rip Her to Shreds." Blondie is for the most part a playful exploration of Sixties pop interlarded with trendy nihilism. Everything is sung by Deborah Harry, possessor of a bombshell zombie's voice that can sound dreamily seductive and woodenly Mansonite within the same song. It's an interesting combination and forces all the songs on Blondie to work on at least two levels: as peppy but rough pop, and as distanced, artless avant-rock. The group's original material has no trouble yielding to this malleability of meaning since the songs are so broad in theme — the plots of "Kung Fu Girls," "Rip Her to Shreds" and "The Attack of the Giant Ants" are exactly what their titles suggest: the aural equivalents of tabloid newspapers. Absolutely anything, from joke to political manifesto to hoax, can be ascribed to them. Two things save Blondie's music from a lack of focus and sincerity. One is producer Richard Gottehrer's adroit echoing of decade-old pop songs, replete with hooks and innocent melodrama. The other is Deborah Harry's utter aplomb and involvement throughout: even when she's portraying a character consummately obnoxious and spaced-out, there is a wink of awareness that is comforting and amusing yet never condescending.

The Ramones' second album contains 14 songs, all around two minutes long. So did their first. They have lost none of their intensity, and if to "leave home" implies a certain broadening of experience, its main evidence on the new record is an occasional use of harmony and the boys' discovery of carbona ("Carbona Not Glue"), a substitute for airplane glue in getting high.

The Ramones are as direct and witty as before. They've also lost just a pinch of their studied rawness: whether this is a sign of maturity or sellout is a matter for debate. The Ramones make rousing music and damn good jokes, but they're in a bind: the hard rock of this group is so pure it may be perceived as a freak novelty by an awful lot of people.

Marquee Moon, Television's debut album, is the most interesting and audacious of this triad, and the most unsettling. Leader Tom Verlaine wrote all the songs, coproduced with Andy Johns, plays lead guitar in a harrowingly mesmerizing stream-of-nightmare style and sings all his verses like an intelligent chicken being strangled: clearly, he dominates this quartet. Television is his vehicle for the portrayal of an arid, despairing sensibility, musically rendered by loud, stark repetitive guitar riffs that build in every one of Marquee Moon's eight songs to nearly out-of-control climaxes. The songs often concern concepts or inanimate objects — "Friction," "Elevation," "Venus" (de Milo, that is) — and when pressed Verlaine even opts for the mechanical over the natural: in the title song, he doesn't think that a movie marquee glows like the moon; he feels that the moon resonates with the same evocative force as a movie marquee.

When one can make out the lyrics, they often prove to be only non sequiturs, or phrases that fit metrically but express little, or puffy aphorisms or chants. (The chorus of "Prove It" repeats, to a delightful sprung-reggae beat: "Prove it/Just the facts/The confidential" a few times.)

All this could serve to distance or repel us, and taken with Verlaine's guitar solos, which flirt with an improvisational formlessness, could easily bore. But he structures his compositions around these spooky, spare riffs, and they stick to the back of your skull. On Marquee Moon, Verlaine becomes all that much better for a new commercial impulse that gives his music its catchy, if slashing, hook.

Television treks across the same cluttered, hostile terrain as bands like the Velvet Underground and the New York Dolls, but the times may be on the side of Verlaine: we have been prepared for Television's harsh subway sound by a grudging, after-the-fact-of-their-careers acceptance of those older bands.

At their best, these three bands do indeed have things in common: a lack of pretension plus an abundance of vigor and adventurousness that have obviously been stoked by popular manifestations of print, film and TV: comic books, detective stories, science fiction, westerns and their attendant stock figures — hoods, dicks, cowboys, aliens: heroes, super and anti. Rock has always traded on a certain amount of this spirit — the naming of a band is just as stirring to its members as the sewing of his first cape is to a fresh superhero — but these three bands use this popular art in a way very few rock & rollers have done — with consistency and accuracy. (The Kiss boys read comics and even dress like them, but their secret identities are those of four businessmen dedicated to taking as few risks as possible.) The Dolls did a bangup job on a song like "Bad Detective" but they never approached the sinister precision Tom Verlaine achieves to wrap up the scenario of "Torn Curtain"; "Prove It" is a paean to a never elucidated "case" Detective Tom has "been workin' on so long." Blondie owes its moniker no less to its peroxide-soaked lead singer than to the marriage partner of Dagwood Bumstead. But in the wisecracking snipes of Deborah Harry, the band knows damn well it has found an image closer to that of a feminist Marvel Comic for the ears. The brutality and willful cruelty of the Ramones' music can find its direct antecedent in the films of Samuel Fuller; Joey Ramone writhing out "Commando" is the real soundtrack for Fuller's yahoo, prowar nose-thumber, Steel Helmet.

The lyrics of these bands are rather beside the point — they are drowned out by the instruments and secondary to the gradations of angst projected by all three lead singers' technically poor voices. But the best of the few lyrics one can decipher have a pulpy richness — certainly not conventional rock sentiments or even examples of "good writing." Verlaine yowls: "I remember/How the darkness doubled/I recall/Lightning struck itself." Is this profound imagery, or just a particularly ripe balloon of dialogue from a Silver Surfer comic book? I would tend toward the latter opinion, even as I am convinced that the song, "Marquee Moon," is a small masterpiece, and the album a medium-sized one.
~ Ken Tucker (April 7, 1977)

The Ramones make rousing music and damn good jokes, but they're in a bind: the hard rock of this group is so pure it may be perceived as a freak novelty by an awful lot of people.

Marquee Moon, Television's debut album, is the most interesting and audacious of this triad, and the most unsettling. Leader Tom Verlaine wrote all the songs, coproduced with Andy Johns, plays lead guitar in a harrowingly mesmerizing stream-of-nightmare style and sings all his verses like an intelligent chicken being strangled: clearly, he dominates this quartet. Television is his vehicle for the portrayal of an arid, despairing sensibility, musically rendered by loud, stark repetitive guitar riffs that build in every one of Marquee Moon's eight songs to nearly out-of-control climaxes. The songs often concern concepts or inanimate objects — "Friction," "Elevation," "Venus" (de Milo, that is) — and when pressed Verlaine even opts for the mechanical over the natural: in the title song, he doesn't think that a movie marquee glows like the moon; he feels that the moon resonates with the same evocative force as a movie marquee.

When one can make out the lyrics, they often prove to be only non sequiturs, or phrases that fit metrically but express little, or puffy aphorisms or chants. (The chorus of "Prove It" repeats, to a delightful sprung-reggae beat: "Prove it/Just the facts/The confidential" a few times.)

All this could serve to distance or repel us, and taken with Verlaine's guitar solos, which flirt with an improvisational formlessness, could easily bore. But he structures his compositions around these spooky, spare riffs, and they stick to the back of your skull. On Marquee Moon, Verlaine becomes all that much better for a new commercial impulse that gives his music its catchy, if slashing, hook.

Television treks across the same cluttered, hostile terrain as bands like the Velvet Underground and the New York Dolls, but the times may be on the side of Verlaine: we have been prepared for Television's harsh subway sound by a grudging, after-the-fact-of-their-careers acceptance of those older bands.

At their best, these three bands do indeed have things in common: a lack of pretension plus an abundance of vigor and adventurousness that have obviously been stoked by popular manifestations of print, film and TV: comic books, detective stories, science fiction, westerns and their attendant stock figures — hoods, dicks, cowboys, aliens: heroes, super and anti. Rock has always traded on a certain amount of this spirit — the naming of a band is just as stirring to its members as the sewing of his first cape is to a fresh superhero — but these three bands use this popular art in a way very few rock & rollers have done — with consistency and accuracy. (The Kiss boys read comics and even dress like them, but their secret identities are those of four businessmen dedicated to taking as few risks as possible.) The Dolls did a bangup job on a song like "Bad Detective" but they never approached the sinister precision Tom Verlaine achieves to wrap up the scenario of "Torn Curtain"; "Prove It" is a paean to a never elucidated "case" Detective Tom has "been workin' on so long." Blondie owes its moniker no less to its peroxide-soaked lead singer than to the marriage partner of Dagwood Bumstead. But in the wisecracking snipes of Deborah Harry, the band knows damn well it has found an image closer to that of a feminist Marvel Comic for the ears. The brutality and willful cruelty of the Ramones' music can find its direct antecedent in the films of Samuel Fuller; Joey Ramone writhing out "Commando" is the real soundtrack for Fuller's yahoo, prowar nose-thumber, Steel Helmet.

The lyrics of these bands are rather beside the point — they are drowned out by the instruments and secondary to the gradations of angst projected by all three lead singers' technically poor voices. But the best of the few lyrics one can decipher have a pulpy richness — certainly not conventional rock sentiments or even examples of "good writing." Verlaine yowls: "I remember/How the darkness doubled/I recall/Lightning struck itself." Is this profound imagery, or just a particularly ripe balloon of dialogue from a Silver Surfer comic book? I would tend toward the latter opinion, even as I am convinced that the song, "Marquee Moon," is a small masterpiece, and the album a medium-sized one.
~ Ken Tucker (April 7, 1977)

tumblr.body:
batmanisagatewaydrug:

I don’t really meta or anything, but I just need to talk about how fascinated I am by Peggy Carter’s fighting style, namely the fact that it is completely fucking brutal.

Peggy Carter doesn’t fight in the graceful and acrobatic and decidedly feminine way Natasha does; Peggy Carter just bulldozes whoever is standing in her way. Peggy throws men through windows and stabs them through the hand to pin them to moving trucks and threatens to kill them for being misogynistic assholes to her friends. She points guns at men standing in front of a whole truck full of explosives. She knocks them unconscious with STAPLERS. 

And none of this is new to the show, either; Peggy has always been this way. In First Avenger she socked the first man to question her authority in the jaw without a second thought; she charged into the final battle against the Red Skull with a machine gun and firing like there was no tomorrow. Hell, she was down with firing at Steve when she thought he was having a fling behind her back.

Peggy Carter is brutally and unapologetically violent in a way that most of the other heroes in Marvel just aren’t, and she was that way long before she met Steve. It just speaks of so much anger and frustration bottled up inside her that comes out through excessively violent combat and I am thrilled by it.

erebusodora:

msgryz:

the-cellist-in-portland:

Did you know: Chris Evans gets panic attacks. Yes, he does. This is one reason why he’s very private and didn’t really do any meet-and-greets on the Avengers’ sets.

It amazes and inspired me that a man who does what he does can do it, even with an anxiety disorder. You go, Chris.

This is why I get so upset when I hear negative comments about Chris and how he doesn’t seem as out-going as the rest of the Avengers cast. I remember hearing people complain about how he’s ‘rude’ and the like and it’s sad, because I highly doubt he intends to come off that way, he’s just more reserved than the others.

I remember hearing once that he actually went to seek psychiatric help before accepting the role of Captain America because of how anxious he felt regarding it. As well as the fact that he already played another Marvel superhero and he was concerned how comic fans would react to his playing another hero in that universe.

Just because someone’s in the entertainment industry doesn’t mean they’re going to be incredibly outgoing off camera just as much as they appear to be on camera. Some people just really enjoy acting; they’re not the characters they portray nor are they like their costars nor are they going to be incredibly outgoing because of their choice of career.

Now I’m really starting to root for this guy. Because, well. I kind of get the point more accurately than I wish I did.

faragonart:

jackthevulture:

Read More

I know this feeling all too well…. 

I won’t get into detail, cause I don’t want to make it about me… but I recently got into an intense fight because of this exact thing…. 

All I want to say is that you are not the only one, and I am glad you are the way you are, and if you are ever pushed into that corner (Gods forbid), I hope to be there to stand up for you, and anyone else who faces this. Cause no one should ever feel guilty for something they love. Don’t ever let anyone make you think/do otherwise (though I feel you might already know that….)

p.s. I always was, and still am, the “dragon girl/lady”. And I know a lot of people did it to make fun of me (added “Weird” or “crazy” in front of the name) But I’m proud of it and I stand up for it with a ”You’re damn right I’m the dragon girl!” So I guess I’m trying to say that it’s alright to be the dragon girl/guy, horse girl/guy, anything. You should OWN THE NAME! Hell, let’s be “dragon girls” TOGETHER!

Be proud of who you are, cause I am proud of you, and how far you have gotten! Keep it up, friend!

Yes to everything above. I understand what you mean about feeling a little awkward about it… but I hope that it turns into pride. You’re awesome. Totally. And we’re all here supporting you.

I feel there’s a point in time where obsessions/fanning/whatever become “cool” rather than a negative judgment. I was the weird “nature kid” in elementary, the “Trekkie” in high school, and what have you… but the older I’ve gotten, the more I’ve seen GOOD things come out of the fandom-centric things I do. I am not wanting to make this conversation about me… but I just want to share my own experiences if that’s okay and say that there’s lots of fun to be had expressing yourself as the “dragon lady”!

I will admit my family is great. My parents don’t get the craziness my sister and I do, but at least they enjoy watching Marvel movies and Star Trek and Lord of the Rings like we do. And though I get some eyebrow raises at the cost or time commitment of my cosplays, my family has no problem saying, “Yeah! Look at this picture of my kids. They’re dressed as the Winter Soldier and Hiccup.”

And this nerd self-expression is where I’ve found really amazing communities, be it online or in real life. I walk into classes wearing a Pinkie and the Brain / Star Wars crossover t-shirt, or an Iron Man shirt, or what have you, and I don’t get weird looks even though everyone knows I am obsessed. Odin, I walk into my graduate classes wearing Hiccup clothes and even braiding my hair like him sometimes, and people just go with it. They see the Doctor Who and Firefly buttons on my backpack and it becomes a point of conversation. A way I make friends. More people treat me as “cool” for my geekdom than “weird”.

The community of fandoms is a wonderful subculture. All my friends and I are the same and just show off who we are. My sister and I have cosplays and put action figures and comic books on our birthday lists. People walking into my condo see an explosion of nerd absolutely everywhere… and tell me they want to make their home someday look just as fandom-decked-out as mine.

Sure, when I was younger, people definitely thought I was strange. In high school, I didn’t care anymore, but I know people thought I was strange there, too. In college, people still likely think I am a bit strange. My parents are fine with it but aren’t submerged in the culture of it. But because I have a whole community of friends like this, it’s totally fine. It’s not seen as childish. It’s seen as cool.

I can say, “Let’s do a Marvel movie marathon night. Costumes encouraged!” and people react with enthusiasm. Not, “weirdo.”

People see my plethora of HTTYD dragons on my bookshelf and think it’s great.

I’m an adult and I’m an obsessed fan. And it’s the way I can make friends, enjoy times with friends, and express myself!

So for me, it’s now an expression of pride, and I really have zero reservation walking down the street wearing Edward Elric’s red jacket or walking into a bank dressed as Bilbo Baggins. There really aren’t as many people as expected giving me second glances, and those that do I find a point of entertainment rather than embarrassment.

It looks like your family is cool with your Dragons love, even if they aren’t involved in it. And the people important in your life methinks are probably cool with it. In the end, that’s what matters and what really makes the big experiences of our lives.

Rules: Always post the rules. Answer the questions the person who tagged you asked, then write 11 new ones.

Thanks faceofthebovvered for tagging me :D

1. Least favourite character from The Hobbit?

Film or book? Film: Alfrid. Book: hnnng this is difficult.

2. Least favourite character from Harry Potter?

Dolores Umbridge. Even though she’s the character we all love to hate.

3. Least favourite character from Marvel?

The Color Purple by Alice Walker. I’d seen the film before reading the book, but the book made a much bigger impact on me.

Get my bachelor’s degree.

I last cooked stuff to put in a tortilla, and I last baked cupcakes.

tumblr.caption:
ungoliantschilde:

cover art for Loki #s 1-4, by Esad Ribic.

Robert Rodi wrote this 4-Issue mini, and Esad provided the fully-painted interior artwork. the series is (essentially) a look at the relationship between Thor and his half-brother, Loki Laufeyson. this story is from Loki’s point of view, and it casts him in a much more understandable light than in previous incarnations. Esad Ribic is in absolutely top-form for this series. this miniseries is actually the first time I personally noticed his work as being something to look for on the shelves.

I subsequently followed him from this to ‘Silver Surfer: Requiem’ with J. Michael Straczynski, and ‘Sub-Mariner: the Depths’ with Peter Milligan.

for the art history fans out there, it bears noting that I spoke with Esad at the NYCC in 2006 or 2007 about this series in particular, and his cover art for Marvel in general. during the conversation, Esad specifically and repeatedly mentioned N.C. Wyeth as a major influence on his painted artwork, especially for the Loki miniseries.

so, by all means, check my blog for the ‘N.C. Wyeth’ tag!

tumblr.body:
batmanisagatewaydrug:

I don’t really meta or anything, but I just need to talk about how fascinated I am by Peggy Carter’s fighting style, namely the fact that it is completely fucking brutal.

Peggy Carter doesn’t fight in the graceful and acrobatic and decidedly feminine way Natasha does; Peggy Carter just bulldozes whoever is standing in her way. Peggy throws men through windows and stabs them through the hand to pin them to moving trucks and threatens to kill them for being misogynistic assholes to her friends. She points guns at men standing in front of a whole truck full of explosives. She knocks them unconscious with STAPLERS. 

And none of this is new to the show, either; Peggy has always been this way. In First Avenger she socked the first man to question her authority in the jaw without a second thought; she charged into the final battle against the Red Skull with a machine gun and firing like there was no tomorrow. Hell, she was down with firing at Steve when she thought he was having a fling behind her back.

Peggy Carter is brutally and unapologetically violent in a way that most of the other heroes in Marvel just aren’t, and it she was that way long before she met Steve. It just speaks of so much anger and frustration bottled up inside her that comes out through excessively violent combat and I am thrilled by it.

Peggy Carter is brutally and unapologetically violent in a way that most of the other heroes in Marvel just aren’t, and it she was that way long before she met Steve. It just speaks of so much anger and frustration bottled up inside her that comes out through excessively violent combat and I am thrilled by it.

jackthevulture:

Read More

I know this feeling all too well…. 

I won’t get into detail, cause I don’t want to make it about me… but I recently got into an intense fight because of this exact thing…. 

All I want to say is that you are not the only one, and I am glad you are the way you are, and if you are ever pushed into that corner (Gods forbid), I hope to be there to stand up for you, and anyone else who faces this. Cause no one should ever feel guilty for something they love. Don’t ever let anyone make you think/do otherwise (though I feel you might already know that….)

p.s. I always was, and still am, the “dragon girl/lady”. And I know a lot of people did it to make fun of me (added “Weird” or “crazy” in front of the name) But I’m proud of it and I stand up for it with a ”You’re damn right I’m the dragon girl!” So I guess I’m trying to say that it’s alright to be the dragon girl/guy, horse girl/guy, anything. You should OWN THE NAME! Hell, let’s be “dragon girls” TOGETHER!

Be proud of who you are, cause I am proud of you, and how far you have gotten! Keep it up, friend!

Yes to everything above. I understand what you mean about feeling a little awkward about it… but I hope that it turns into pride. You’re awesome. Totally. And we’re all here supporting you.

I feel there’s a point in time where obsessions/fanning/whatever become “cool” rather than a negative judgment. I was the weird “nature kid” in elementary, the “Trekkie” in high school, and what have you… but the older I’ve gotten, the more I’ve seen GOOD things come out of the fandom-centric things I do. I am not wanting to make this conversation about me… but I just want to share my own experiences if that’s okay and say that there’s lots of fun to be had expressing yourself as the “dragon lady”!

I will admit my family is great. My parents don’t get the craziness my sister and I do, but at least they enjoy watching Marvel movies and Star Trek and Lord of the Rings like we do. And though I get some eyebrow raises at the cost or time commitment of my cosplays, my family has no problem saying, “Yeah! Look at this picture of my kids. They’re dressed as the Winter Soldier and Hiccup.”

And this nerd self-expression is where I’ve found really amazing communities, be it online or in real life. I walk into classes wearing a Pinkie and the Brain / Star Wars crossover t-shirt, or an Iron Man shirt, or what have you, and I don’t get weird looks even though everyone knows I am obsessed. Odin, I walk into my graduate classes wearing Hiccup clothes and even braiding my hair like him sometimes, and people just go with it. They see the Doctor Who and Firefly buttons on my backpack and it becomes a point of conversation. A way I make friends. More people treat me as “cool” for my geekdom than “weird”.

The community of fandoms is a wonderful subculture. All my friends and I are the same and just show off who we are. My sister and I have cosplays and put action figures and comic books on our birthday lists. People walking into my condo see an explosion of nerd absolutely everywhere… and tell me they want to make their home someday look just as fandom-decked-out as mine.

Sure, when I was younger, people definitely thought I was strange. In high school, I didn’t care anymore, but I know people thought I was strange there, too. In college, people still likely think I am a bit strange. My parents are fine with it but aren’t submerged in the culture of it. But because I have a whole community of friends like this, it’s totally fine. It’s not seen as childish. It’s seen as cool.

I can say, “Let’s do a Marvel movie marathon night. Costumes encouraged!” and people react with enthusiasm. Not, “weirdo.”

People see my plethora of HTTYD dragons on my bookshelf and think it’s great.

I’m an adult and I’m an obsessed fan. And it’s the way I can make friends, enjoy times with friends, and express myself!

So for me, it’s now an expression of pride, and I really have zero reservation walking down the street wearing Edward Elric’s red jacket or walking into a bank dressed as Bilbo Baggins. There really aren’t as many people as expected giving me second glances, and those that do I find a point of entertainment rather than embarrassment.

It looks like your family is cool with your Dragons love, even if they aren’t involved in it. And the people important in your life methinks are probably cool with it. In the end, that’s what matters and what really makes the big experiences of our lives.

ryannorth:

Our first issue is out today!!  You can get Unbeatable Squirrel Girl at your local comic book store, you can download a digital copy RIGHT NOW, and/or you can get them in the mail!  DID YOU KNOW: the more copies we sell (whether physical or digital), the better chance we have of getting to make this comic forever and ever??

And on the off chance you don’t want to risk getting this book without some non-me people telling you they think the book is PRETTY OKAY, I have some good news!  Here’s a…

REVIEW ROUNDUP

COMICOSITY:

One word: adorbs.

OK, I’ll throw in a few more words. How about super-fun? Or unexpected? Or laugh-out-loud funny?

Some of those are compounds.

COMIC VINE:

Expectations were pretty high for this first issue but THE UNBEATABLE SQUIRREL GIRL exceeds them. North, Henderson, and Renzi have put together something that appeals to both young and old that is an incredible amount of fun, featuring a great, stand-out star…

THE BEAT:

…fun is no longer such a terrible word.The Unbeatable Squirrel Girl is a product of this shift, something steadfast and confident in its construction and delivery, an unapologetic take on the pyjama drama as a source of unfettered joy. 

CBR:

There are few “perfect issues” in a year of comics and yet here I am, first week of January writing about another one… There is not one missed or false note, it’s a totally cohesive vision. Everyone creating this book knows exactly what they want it to be and exactly how to get it there.

COMICBOOK.COM

…one of the most fun debuts published by Marvel Comics in a very long time. If you’re looking for a comic that you can share with anyone or that will cheer you up after a major bummer of a day, this is it. At the end of The Unbeatable Squirrel Girl #1 there is only one question worth asking: When does #2 come out?

I hope you enjoy the book!  Next month even crazier things happen.  UNTIL THEN I PROPOSE WE ALL:

  1. EAT NUTS
  2. KICK BUTTS

laaaaavender:

im angry at marvel for not representing the lgbt community. how hard is it to make a gender fluid shape shifter or a gay guy with fire powers????

It would be literally the easiest thing in the whole world for Marvel to include more queer, trans and genderfluid characters in their comics

The fact that they don’t isn’t because they can’t or that it’s somehow difficult for them to do so, it’s because Marvel and the ‘writers’ (Using that word VERY loosely) who work for them don’t want to

Hence why I no longer buy ANYTHING Marvel related nor intend to

I thought Mistque was gender fluid

No but there have occasionally be implications that she’s a trans woman…naturally Marvel have never made this canon though :(

Fuck yaa it would be awesome if she was

My headcanon for Mystique will ALWAYS be that she’s an awesome bad ass trans woman <3 

Personally, I headcanon Emma Frost as trans. Apparently there were some comics about her backstory where she related having had a gay brother who basically disappeared to a psychiatric hospital after being effectively disowned by the family, which happened immediately before or at the same time that Emma left. I thought it would be interesting if the brother was actually her metaphor for herself pre-transition.

I LOVE this headcanon for Emma Frost and love the idea of her being an amazing trans woman because I basically love everything about Emma’s character and the idea of her being like me makes me feel really nice inside…

I wish there was a chance of this becoming canon and us getting Emma as a bad ass diamond skinned trans lady in the comics…

I think it would fit her character too with things like the way she takes a special interest in the students she teaches…their feelings of not feeling comfortable in their own bodies, in their case because of coming to terms with being a mutant, is probably something Emma would be able to relate to a lot…

I feel like I read this before.

tumblr.body:
batmanisagatewaydrug:

I don’t really meta or anything, but I just need to talk about how fascinated I am by Peggy Carter’s fighting style, namely the fact that it is completely fucking brutal.

Peggy Carter doesn’t fight in the graceful and acrobatic and decidedly feminine way Natasha does; Peggy Carter just bulldozes whoever is standing in her way. Peggy throws men through windows and stabs them through the hand to pin them to moving trucks and threatens to kill them for being misogynistic assholes to her friends. She points guns at men standing in front of a whole truck full of explosives. She knocks them unconscious with STAPLERS. 

And none of this is new to the show, either; Peggy has always been this way. In First Avenger she socked the first man to question her authority in the jaw without a second thought; she charged into the final battle against the Red Skull with a machine gun and firing like there was no tomorrow. Hell, she was down with firing at Steve when she thought he was having a fling behind her back.

Peggy Carter is brutally and unapologetically violent in a way that most of the other heroes in Marvel just aren’t, and it she was that way long before she met Steve. It just speaks of so much anger and frustration bottled up inside her that comes out through excessively violent combat and I am thrilled by it.

facebook.message:
Superhero News. News and positive reactions from Tokusatsu Spider-Man's appearance in the recent issue of Amazing Spider-Man has prompted Marvel to have all 41 episodes of the 1978 Japanese live-action series (produced by Toei of DBZ fame) available on their website.

http://marvel.com/news/comics/23916/japanese_spiderman_rocks_spider-verse_returns_to_marvelcom

In Addition, Marvel staff member Tom Brevoort has said that if fans demand it, Marvel will produce a comic book series based on Tokusatsu Spider-Man. Marvel is also hoping that the upcoming Spider-Verse Team-Up issue featuring Mayday Parker/Spider-Girl will sell just as well as Spider-Gwen to convince Marvel to relaunch the fan favorite series.

http://brevoortformspring.tumblr.com/post/107671395443/hello-tom-apperance-of-leopardon-in-asm-12-making

The Beast Premium Format by Sideshow Collectibles

This maquette is an early study of how the Beast might translate from 2D to 3D for X-Men: The Last Stand. Sideshow is proud to offer this first rendition in the long creative process of bringing this character to life on the big screen. 

Though covered in blue fur, and animal in appearance, the addition of the glasses and the book gives Beast and amazing feel of intelligence.

Sideshow Collectibles and Spectral Motion present a reproduction of the original maquette created during pre-production work on the film. Translating Beast from comic to film was particularly challenging, as Beast's appearance has varied greatly over his Marvel lifespan. 

The team at Spectral Motion crafted a look that is immediately identifiable as Beast, but also allows Hank McCoy's intelligence to radiate through the blue fur and the leonine visage. 

The Beast Maquette is a strikingly successful blend of Beast and McCoy, complete with sagely glasses and book in hand, sure to be the centerpiece of any X-collection.

tumblr.body:
still-marauding:

okay okay there was like nothing out there (mostly homophobic forums denouncing the very idea of queer heroes) but I found what I could

the basics:

chris evans has said that his captain america is bisexual (but I couldn’t find the interview), so I mean, theres that, but heres all this stuff I you don’t believe me:

*chris evans is a vocal queer activist: http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/04/21/chris-evans-on-gay-marriage_n_1442704.html

*and has a gay brother: http://www.eonline.com/photos/3741/celebs-with-gay-siblings/139827

*steve rogers flirts, talks to, and interacts with sam wilson much the same way he does with his former love interest, peggy carter: http://forassgard.tumblr.com/post/84400525544 and http://sorrelrum.tumblr.com/post/83177708060/america-for-a-bisexual-cap

*captain america has a long history of queer acceptance: http://trelkez.tumblr.com/post/28072827300/starring-captain-americas-gay-bff-arnie-roth

*PLUS THIS WONDERFUL THING: http://jamesbucky.co.vu/post/57926740174/chris-why-do-you-feel-like-captain-america-is-the

* the time and place in which steve grew up was very different from what one would expect of the 40’s: http://thingswithwings.dreamwidth.org/213805.html

*here also is a short, incomplete list of actual canon queer heroes in marvel and dc comics: http://www.advocate.com/news/2008/10/22/don%E2%80%99t-mask-do-tell

other queer superheroes include kate bishop, aka Hawkeye, and america chavez, aka Miss America

*unrelated to cap, andrew garfield is ready and willing to see more queer superheroes, including spider-man: http://www.dailydot.com/geek/andrew-garfield-plugs-bisexual-peter-parker/

its not fanfiction and fanart and hollow “everyone is equal” quotes anymore, this is real stuff, this is tangible change, people are noticing and something has got to give sooner or later

tumblr.caption:
vixyish:

ellidfics:

cecilyjeanne:

devil-whore-bitch:

They’ve got civilians trapped.

I love that while the avengers fought the aliens you also see them helping to evacuate people so they are safe. It’s not just fighting, it’s rescue as well.

YES THANK YOU! This was my huge and horrible problem with Man of Steel. No help. Buildings falling left and right. I just kept saying “There’s another 10,000 dead people…oooh, and another 10,000 right there!” And no one cared. It left me feeling a bit sick, actually.

In the same movie Captain American *repeatedly* goes out of his way to rescue civilians, order the local police to make sure that the civilians are safe, tells people to get underground in a deleted scene, and leaves the main battle to rescue an entire bank full of terrified people from the Chitauri.  He damn near gets blown to pieces doing the last, after losing his cowl so that the entire world can see his face and realize that the guy in the Captain America outfit is the lost hero from 1945 who sacrificed himself to save the entire Eastern Seaboard.  

Want more?  Don’t forget that Thor offers himself to save an entire town of people he doesn’t even know, and that a couple of years later Jane runs through a library screaming at people to get away from Malekith and his ships as they ravage Greenwich.  And what the Guardians of the Galaxy and the Nova Corps banding together to save an entire planet?  Tony Stark sending his precious armor to save Pepper, then ordering her to remove Maya from the battle zone before thinking of himself?  Bruce Banner going underground to heal people in the most literal sense?  Sharon Carter taking the extra second to kick the launch technician’s chair out from under him just in time to prevent Crossbones from blowing him to hell?  All those poor doomed SHIELD agents trying to take on STRIKE teams with hand guns to prevent those helicarriers from getting intot he air?

Best of all, after spending two years working beside Cap and going on the lam with him, Black Widow, the most morally ambiguous character of them all, shouts “Get out of the way!  RUN!” as she flees for her life from the Winter Soldier.  This is a woman who a worldwide reputation for black ops, and even she puts non-combatants above her own life.

It’s one of the things I love best about Marvel:  their characters are more than muscle and speed and grandstanding against impossible odds.  They have heart and soul and spirit, and every single one of them, without exception, is willing to take the extra second or two to protect the innocent and the defenseless even if it means their own lives.  There’s a moral core there that the Superman of Man of Steel lacks, and it’s a reason why these movies are so popular:

We know in our bones that if we lived in their universe, they’d do what true heroes do, and they’d save us.  

Superman, at least in Man of Steel, doesn’t.  

That makes all the difference.

Also why Christopher Reeve is and will always be my Superman.

tumblr.caption:
l0kasenna:

zombres:

tom-sits-like-a-whore:

Okay. But let’s talk about Thor for a second. Thor does not get enough love and (Loki forgive me) he is honestly one of the best fucking characters Marvel has. And it’s shown so simply and so beautifully right here. He is so fucking chill about everything. Obviously, he doesn’t live in space, he lives in Asgard. But he knows everyone thinks he’s kinda like an alien, and he just goes along with it because why not? These humans are funny in their lack of understanding, but it’s an endearing kind of funny. Just like in the first movie, where Darcy tells him to smile so she can take a picture of him and he has no fucking clue what she’s doing or what a phone is and it could kill him for all he knows but he just fucking smiles and keeps eating his delicious pancakes because he’s just so chill like that. And if you look at his face in the first gif, it’s very serious and concentrated but the moment Darcy starts talking to him he loosens up and is like “Muscles? Ah, yes I suppose I am quite muscular. Oh, she’s inquiring about Asgard. But she called it space. She seems confused as to my origins, but it’s not of import. I like space, that’s a good name. I shall call it space too.”

And that little head nod he does back to her in the last gif. I’m dead. Deceased. Murdered from Thor cuteness. 

He’s just.. ugh, Thor doesn’t get enough appreciation. There are so many little things he does that go ignored but no more. His complete adorableness will be appreciated. 

#HOW DO YOU HATE THE ASGARDIAN EMBODIMENT OF SUNSHINE AND JOY?

I DIDN’T NOTICE THE LITTLE NOD BACK /SCREEEEEEEEE

tumblr.caption:
vixyish:

ellidfics:

cecilyjeanne:

devil-whore-bitch:

They’ve got civilians trapped.

I love that while the avengers fought the aliens you also see them helping to evacuate people so they are safe. It’s not just fighting, it’s rescue as well.

YES THANK YOU! This was my huge and horrible problem with Man of Steel. No help. Buildings falling left and right. I just kept saying “There’s another 10,000 dead people…oooh, and another 10,000 right there!” And no one cared. It left me feeling a bit sick, actually.

In the same movie Captain American *repeatedly* goes out of his way to rescue civilians, order the local police to make sure that the civilians are safe, tells people to get underground in a deleted scene, and leaves the main battle to rescue an entire bank full of terrified people from the Chitauri.  He damn near gets blown to pieces doing the last, after losing his cowl so that the entire world can see his face and realize that the guy in the Captain America outfit is the lost hero from 1945 who sacrificed himself to save the entire Eastern Seaboard.  

Want more?  Don’t forget that Thor offers himself to save an entire town of people he doesn’t even know, and that a couple of years later Jane runs through a library screaming at people to get away from Malekith and his ships as they ravage Greenwich.  And what the Guardians of the Galaxy and the Nova Corps banding together to save an entire planet?  Tony Stark sending his precious armor to save Pepper, then ordering her to remove Maya from the battle zone before thinking of himself?  Bruce Banner going underground to heal people in the most literal sense?  Sharon Carter taking the extra second to kick the launch technician’s chair out from under him just in time to prevent Crossbones from blowing him to hell?  All those poor doomed SHIELD agents trying to take on STRIKE teams with hand guns to prevent those helicarriers from getting intot he air?

Best of all, after spending two years working beside Cap and going on the lam with him, Black Widow, the most morally ambiguous character of them all, shouts “Get out of the way!  RUN!” as she flees for her life from the Winter Soldier.  This is a woman who a worldwide reputation for black ops, and even she puts non-combatants above her own life.

It’s one of the things I love best about Marvel:  their characters are more than muscle and speed and grandstanding against impossible odds.  They have heart and soul and spirit, and every single one of them, without exception, is willing to take the extra second or two to protect the innocent and the defenseless even if it means their own lives.  There’s a moral core there that the Superman of Man of Steel lacks, and it’s a reason why these movies are so popular:

We know in our bones that if we lived in their universe, they’d do what true heroes do, and they’d save us.  

Superman, at least in Man of Steel, doesn’t.  

That makes all the difference.

Also why Christopher Reeve is and will always be my Superman.

tumblr.caption:
comixology:

ryannorth:

Our first issue is out today!!  You can get Unbeatable Squirrel Girl at your local comic book store, you can download a digital copy RIGHT NOW, and/or you can get them in the mail!  DID YOU KNOW: the more copies we sell (whether physical or digital), the better chance we have of getting to make this comic forever and ever??

And on the off chance you don’t want to risk getting this book without some non-me people telling you they think the book is PRETTY OKAY, I have some good news!  Here’s a…

REVIEW ROUNDUP

COMICOSITY:

One word: adorbs.

OK, I’ll throw in a few more words. How about super-fun? Or unexpected? Or laugh-out-loud funny?

Some of those are compounds.

COMIC VINE:

Expectations were pretty high for this first issue but THE UNBEATABLE SQUIRREL GIRL exceeds them. North, Henderson, and Renzi have put together something that appeals to both young and old that is an incredible amount of fun, featuring a great, stand-out star…

THE BEAT:

…fun is no longer such a terrible word.The Unbeatable Squirrel Girl is a product of this shift, something steadfast and confident in its construction and delivery, an unapologetic take on the pyjama drama as a source of unfettered joy. 

CBR:

There are few “perfect issues” in a year of comics and yet here I am, first week of January writing about another one… There is not one missed or false note, it’s a totally cohesive vision. Everyone creating this book knows exactly what they want it to be and exactly how to get it there.

COMICBOOK.COM

…one of the most fun debuts published by Marvel Comics in a very long time. If you’re looking for a comic that you can share with anyone or that will cheer you up after a major bummer of a day, this is it. At the end of The Unbeatable Squirrel Girl #1 there is only one question worth asking: When does #2 come out?

I hope you enjoy the book!  Next month even crazier things happen.  UNTIL THEN I PROPOSE WE ALL:

  1. EAT NUTS
  2. KICK BUTTS

Too cold to go outside and get it? Read it instantly right here!

Too lazy to go outside and get it? …It’s still right here!

tumblr.caption:
littlenormandy:

relax-o-vision:

anothergayshark:

It’s sad that these are actually in the order that they were written. 

The thing with Glee is that you can take single scenes and marvel at their love for details and the idea behind the entire set-up and oftentimes even the dialogue. 

But if you put those scenes together and look at the context everything just loses logic. Dialogues suddenly sound like random slogans about friendship and sticking together, stolen from movie trailers. Characters lose all depth, all personality, because they’re meant to exist in the vortex of the single moment, not the broad picture. They don’t have a history.

That’s why you can never tell what a character’s intentions really are. Does Santana care about her education or not? We’ll never know, because the only scene, which had the potential to be a true discussion about her future was cramped into the very last episode in an “oops we forgot that existed, is it too late to address that?” kind of way. Had the very same scene happened five episodes earlier, there had been a chance for an actual story.

But an actual story is not what Glee is interested in.

Glee is about single scenes, in which the actors are sexed up in a way that appeals to the average superficial gay guy’s sense of beauty, showtunes and pseudo intelligent phrases to lecture the audience about right and wrong. 

Oh snap

thefingerfuckingfemalefury:

ayellowbirds:

thefingerfuckingfemalefury:

mutantlexi:

fuckyeahblackwidow:

Jessica: Well, look, I’ve been coming to grips with who I am for a while. I mean… I’ve got somebody else’s memories and feelings to wade through. Am I that person or are these thoughts my own? I can’t complain! I’ve got these awesome powers, this physical ability, I get to… be here, be alive. So yeah, I get into weird territories of what defines the self. Who is the self, even, y’know? I know that sounds all New Age and dumb…
Kitty: It’s not at all dumb.
Jessica: I have a girl’s body, but the brain patterns of a guy… Peter… But I can’t help but feel like I’m developing my own feelings, my own ideas… they may have come from another source, but if these thoughts are unique to me, aren’t they mine then? I don’t want to overthink it. I just want to go to what feels right.
Lana: So… What feels right?
Jessica: Um… girls?
Lana: No kidding.
Jessica: Haha, yeah, girls. Natural redheads in particular.
Kitty: Great.
Jessica: I kinda have a thing for Jewish girls, too.

I wanted to post this sequence in that ask about LBGTQ Black Widow, but it violated my spoiler policy.

From All-New Ultimates #4, by Michel Fiffe and Amilcar Pinna.

While I think it’s cute that Kitty’s a little jealous there, but thinking about it, her reaction kinda bugs me.

Jess is trying to establish herself, her sense of self, and Kitty’s kinda projecting this need for Jess to be Peter’s replacement.

I like to read it as Kitty having feelings for Jess herself rather than seeing her as a replacement for Peter but I know it’s probably wishful thinking on my part that I might hope we’ll get canon queer Kitty Pryde having an actual relationship with Jess…or that we’ll get to see Jess in a relationship with ANY girl for that matter :(

Am I the only person who reads this and wonders why they aren’t exploring Jessica’s gender identity more?

Oh wait, I know why.

"We had her mention she likes girls once on a single page of one issue what more do you people want?

What’s that?

'For us to actually give her storylines in which her sexuality and gender identity plays a part?'

Well now you’re just being unreasonable, here’s twenty two pages of straight cis people in spandex hitting each other in the face instead

Your welcome”

Let’s take a gay ray to the marvel world and go to town.

tumblr.body:
batmanisagatewaydrug:

I don’t really meta or anything, but I just need to talk about how fascinated I am by Peggy Carter’s fighting style, namely the fact that it is completely fucking brutal.

Peggy Carter doesn’t fight in the graceful and acrobatic and decidedly feminine way Natasha does; Peggy Carter just bulldozes whoever is standing in her way. Peggy throws men through windows and stabs them through the hand to pin them to moving trucks and threatens to kill them for being misogynistic assholes to her friends. She points guns at men standing in front of a whole truck full of explosives. She knocks them unconscious with STAPLERS. 

And none of this is new to the show, either; Peggy has always been this way. In First Avenger she socked the first man to question her authority in the jaw without a second thought; she charged into the final battle against the Red Skull with a machine gun and firing like there was no tomorrow. Hell, she was down with firing at Steve when she thought he was having a fling behind her back.

Peggy Carter is brutally and unapologetically violent in a way that most of the other heroes in Marvel just aren’t, and it she was that way long before she met Steve. It just speaks of so much anger and frustration bottled up inside her that comes out through excessively violent combat and I am thrilled by it.

tumblr.caption:
anti-stand-with-ward:

A week designed for people who adore the canonical villain that Ward is to come together and appreciate his vast creepiness.

Day 1: Favorite Villainous Moment
What Ward moment scared you the most? What moment solidified his villainy in your mind? What were your favorite moments of the team reacting to his villainy?

Day 2: Most Badass Moment
A moment Ward gets his ass kicked by somebody he’s wronged

Day 3: Parallels
How does Ward not measure up to other Marvel (or otherwise) heroes? How is he similar to other villains?

Day 4: Why He Doesn’t Deserve Redemption
Talk about the horrible things he has done, and how it makes it clear he is not a good person and doesn’t deserve redemption

Day 5: The Future
What would you like to see happen next?

Day 6: Alternate Universes
Create an AU where Ward meets and works with another villain from the MCU or any other story.

Day 7: Brett Dalton Appreciation
Appreciation for Brett Dalton’s marvelous performances after the Hydra reveal. What moment made you realize how good of an actor he is?

tumblr.caption:
thecomicsvault:

TODAY IN COMIC BOOK HISTORY: January 10, 1962

The original Ant-Man, Dr. Henry Johnathan “Hank” Pym made his debut in Tales To Astonish #27 as a scientist testing a shrinking apparatus on himself and then having to fend off ants until he could return to normal height. The story was more of a sci-fi/horror/fantasy story, which is what TTA was during the transition from the Golden to Silver Age of comics.

Eight issues later, Dr. Pym came back. This time as a superhero using his shrinking technology to fight crime. The addition of a helmet that could communicate and control ants made it so hostile insects were the least of his problems. Ant-Man took over the title full time and soon Pym’s lab assistant and girlfriend, Janet van Dyne aka The Wasp, joined him in #44 and the two spent the next 20+ issues solving crimes. Ant-Man eventually became Giant-Man during their run, one of many of Pym’s aliases.

Pym and van Dyne are founding members of The Avengers and were big parts of the early stories. They left the team briefly only to return for one of the most iconic Avengers stories. Pym was the sole creator of the artificial intelligence known as Ultron. Originally created for non-lethal purposes, Ultron gained sentience and a hatred for all organic life. He became one of Marvel’s biggest villains. Out of that story line also came a new Avenger, The Vision, created by Ultron to defeat The Avengers. He eventually turned on his creator. Ultron and Pym have the strngest father-son relationships in comics.

Hank is also know for his various alter-egos, By the late-60s he had already been Ant-Man, Giant Man and Goliath. The constant shape-changing, overusing his serums and various costumes caused him to develop schizophrenia. In another iconic Avengers story Hank is seemingly killed by a new costumed hero, Yellowkacket. Only The Wasp knew it was really Pym and the two, after years of romantic tension, finally married. 

After taking another break from The Avengers, Pym returns. However his personality has regressed even further. He shows more hostility towards Janet and continues to beat villains after they are defeated. This causes Captain America to suspend him from the team until after the verdict of his court-martial. This pushes Pym to the breaking point and he has a complete mental breakdown. Devising a plan to attack the courthouse during his trial using a robot which he will defeat and make himself look like the hero. Janet discovers his plan and he infamously strikes her.

The two eventually divorce and Pym is takes a break from superheroics for a bit. He then joins the West Coast Avengers before returning to The Avengers. Pym has passed down some of his aliases. First Giant-Man and Goliath to Dr. Bill Foster aka Black Goliath. Next he passed his alter-ego Ant-Man to Scott Lang after he stole the costume and Pym particles to help his daughter. 

Hank Pym has been a part of almost every major Marvel event since the beginning and his influence in the Marvel Universe is far-reaching. He’s one of the great comic book characters to portray the inner conflict of someone who wants to do the right thing but doesn’t always due to mental disorders or misguided intentions. He’s also a great character period.

tumblr.caption:
thecomicsvault:

TODAY IN COMIC BOOK HISTORY: January 10, 1962

The original Ant-Man, Dr. Henry Johnathan “Hank” Pym made his debut in Tales To Astonish #27 as a scientist testing a shrinking apparatus on himself and then having to fend off ants until he could return to normal height. The story was more of a sci-fi/horror/fantasy story, which is what TTA was during the transition from the Golden to Silver Age of comics.

Eight issues later, Dr. Pym came back. This time as a superhero using his shrinking technology to fight crime. The addition of a helmet that could communicate and control ants made it so hostile insects were the least of his problems. Ant-Man took over the title full time and soon Pym’s lab assistant and girlfriend, Janet van Dyne aka The Wasp, joined him in #44 and the two spent the next 20+ issues solving crimes. Ant-Man eventually became Giant-Man during their run, one of many of Pym’s aliases.

Pym and van Dyne are founding members of The Avengers and were big parts of the early stories. They left the team briefly only to return for one of the most iconic Avengers stories. Pym was the sole creator of the artificial intelligence known as Ultron. Originally created for non-lethal purposes, Ultron gained sentience and a hatred for all organic life. He became one of Marvel’s biggest villains. Out of that story line also came a new Avenger, The Vision, created by Ultron to defeat The Avengers. He eventually turned on his creator. Ultron and Pym have the strngest father-son relationships in comics.

Hank is also know for his various alter-egos, By the late-60s he had already been Ant-Man, Giant Man and Goliath. The constant shape-changing, overusing his serums and various costumes caused him to develop schizophrenia. In another iconic Avengers story Hank is seemingly killed by a new costumed hero, Yellowkacket. Only The Wasp knew it was really Pym and the two, after years of romantic tension, finally married. 

After taking another break from The Avengers, Pym returns. However his personality has regressed even further. He shows more hostility towards Janet and continues to beat villains after they are defeated. This causes Captain America to suspend him from the team until after the verdict of his court-martial. This pushes Pym to the breaking point and he has a complete mental breakdown. Devising a plan to attack the courthouse during his trial using a robot which he will defeat and make himself look like the hero. Janet discovers his plan and he infamously strikes her.

The two eventually divorce and Pym is takes a break from superheroics for a bit. He then joins the West Coast Avengers before returning to The Avengers. Pym has passed down some of his aliases. First Giant-Man and Goliath to Dr. Bill Foster aka Black Goliath. Next he passed his alter-ego Ant-Man to Scott Lang after he stole the costume and Pym particles to help his daughter. 

Hank Pym has been a part of almost every major Marvel event since the beginning and his influence in the Marvel Universe is far-reaching. He’s one of the great comic book characters to portray the inner conflict of someone who wants to do the right thing but doesn’t always due to mental disorders or misguided intentions. He’s also a great character period.
